At first glance, I understand MetaHash can be hard to grasp—it may seem circular and weird. It can look like there’s just Alpha flowing around with no real value. But there is!

**Let me use a recent X post to explain this**
    
MetaHash is like an OTC generators between Miners and Validators. So saying there is no value brings the question, why people do OTC deals then? Why funds do OTC deals? Why @dsvfund is doing deals non stop? 

Because it is a win-win scenenario.

Imaging having access to this deals without you having to meet with subnets, trust issues etc. Thats what MetaHash is. 

Lets analyze the sell and buy pressure balance:

There will be sell pressure comming from miners trying to get usd.  Like in any other subnet by the way. 

The buy pressure will come from:

1. Discounted alpha stream comming into validators, sold and going back to the pool in the form of buy backs. 

2. People/validators wanting more sn73 alpha to get access to this alpha streams. Value is being generated as Sum(alpha) > Mining Emissions aka revenue. 

3. Increase in value of locked alpha in validators due to holding, trading or whatever strategy they decide. Same reasoning that with BTC appreaciation in TaoHash. 

Overall you can clearly see MetaHash works as a Fund where the effective price of alpha adquired its less than the market. Sn73 is essentially a decentralized version of what many funds are already doing: making OTC deals with subnets with a discount and then holding and waiting for price appreciation.

There are for sure challenges and premises and I will be posting a long-format post talking about:

1. Inter-validation competition and what they can and should do with the alpha
2. Scalability problem similar to what TaoHash suffers already disccused by Vune and Striker etc...
3. Increasing Liquidity . UniswapV3.
4. Reducing mining dumps and sell pressure.

After long consideration and discussing in private with many of you (thanks a lot for the feedback its truly appreciated), I can say that const argument for simplicity is kind of true, especially in the early stages. Starting with a single shared Alpha basket reduces complexity and helps users clearly understand how everything works. We're going for this approach as the starting point.

That said, looking more into the future of MetaHash, I believe we will inevitably need to implement a more intelligent buy-side mechanism. One that supports asset discrimination and dynamic valuation of Alpha from different subnets. While “putting everything into one basket” offers clarity, it comes at the cost of treating all subnet Alpha as if they were equal — when in reality, even at same price, each represents a fundamentally distinct asset class, with its ow fundmentals and strategic uses. In real OTC markets, buyers don’t blindly accept everything — they carefully evaluate which assets to acquire, what discount is appropriate, and how long they’re willing to hold it etc...

The idea of giving validators more freedom was essentially an attempt to enable price discovery on the buy-side — letting validators signal their preferences by publishing weight curves, which are mappings of the discount (weight) they assign to different Alpha tokens at various lock durations. Something like “I’ll value SN14 at 0.85 if locked for 2 months, or 0.95 if locked for 1 month”. Essentially asking for more discount the more lock period there will be. This allows a Validator to express both asset preference and time preference. Of course all this has to be done while ensuring validators do not hide their actions, not instantly sell the Alpha at the expense of miners and so on ... 
Of course much more risks and complexity than "one basket" design and kind of obvious not go for this for first iteration. However this are some ideas that we could take into consideration for the future.

Although this was pre-dTao world, you still had to manage your operational costs and balance out the costs associated with infrastructure. This added a significant amount of constraints on subnet owners to manage their budgets. The curse of the subnet owner - nobody is expecting you to sell any alpha at any point of time.
